At the end of the exchanges, the Prague stock exchange plunged into the negative
After the fall on Tuesday morning, the Prague Stock Exchange rectified its losses.
Transactions with <0xC4><0x8C>EZ shares reached almost half of the usual daily trades.
On Tuesday, from the beginning of trading, the Prague stock exchange resumed its fall the day before, when it lost almost six percent.
This time, the decline is due to the fall in Wall Street stocks.
The reaction of the market to the result of the vote of the American House of Representatives, which refused to adopt the plan for the stabilization of the American financial sector, is thus also perceptible in our country.
Falling stocks in Asia
Asian stock exchanges suffered a dramatic fall on Tuesday, even though the indices managed, during the day, to erase some of the losses.
The Hong Kong Stock Exchange’s Hang Seng Index lost four percent during trading, but later erased some of the losses and reduced the decline to nearly 2.5 percent.
The Hang Seng China Enterprises index following the movement of Chinese shares on the Hong Kong Stock Exchange lost 3.8 percent, with markets closed in Shanghai.
Sydney Stock Exchange stocks were losing more than five percent, but eventually the losses were reduced to 4.3 percent.
According to its index, the Taiwan Stock Exchange lost 3.6 percent.
“Hesitation about bailout action in the U.S. will affect financial markets around the world,” said Joseph Yam, head of the Hong Kong Monetary Office.
Although Hong Kong is part of China, it establishes its monetary policy itself, i.e. independently of the Chinese central bank.
Interest rates in Hong Kong are at the same level as in the United States.
According to Australian Prime Minister Kevin Rudd, US lawmakers should quickly resume negotiations and adopt the proposal to support the financial system.
Otherwise, there would be a risk that other countries would be affected.
The Bloodbath of American Actions
On Monday, the U.S. House of Representatives rejected the financial system support project, to which it should have spent up to $700 billion (nearly K<0xC4><0x8D> 12 billion).
Legislators dismissed President George Bush’s call for support.
According to Bush, the project should solve the main causes of the financial crisis and help stabilize the entire economy.
U.S. stocks experienced a bloodbath on Monday and major stock indexes experienced the biggest drop in the last 20 years.
The Dow Jones lost nearly seven percent, having experienced such a drop for the last time in 1987.
The index was already losing during the vote, but when it appeared that the proposal was not adopted, it was in free fall.
Congress Gives Up: U.S. Government Can Inject $700 Billion Into Banks
The leaders of the U.S. Congress and the government of President George W. Bush have agreed on a broader form of financial aid agreement for the U.S. financial system.
It will be put to the vote early next week.
U.S. lawmakers were making a turning point in talks to adopt a bailout in the form of $700 billion in financial aid to the U.S. financial system.
However, success is not certain.
Indeed, before the final version of the law can be published and put to a vote, Congressmen must finalize a number of details of the agreement.
The financial system support plan will be discussed in the House of Representatives on Monday.
Barney Frank, chairman of the House Banking and Financial Regulation Committee, told Reuters on Sunday.
According to sources, on Wednesday at the earliest, the plan should a priori be put to a vote in the Senate.
According to economists, the announcement that the bailout will be adopted should be a first major psychological factor in reviving financial markets.
However, given the complexity of the mechanisms by which aid to markets can be effective, a "disillusionment" will follow.
Paulson: The plan must be effective
“We have made great progress.
We have settled our divergent views on the form the package of measures for market stabilization should take," Democratic Nancy Pelosi told Bloomberg.
According to her, the final vote could be taken as early as Sunday.
On the night of Saturday to Sunday, representatives of the legislature met with U.S. Finance Minister Henry Paulson, in order to give the government a final form.
It is expected to buy back unsold real estate assets from financial corporations that cause financial firms to suffer significant losses and threaten the stability of the system as a whole.
“We are about to agree on a plan that will work and must also be effective in the market.
This market recovery plan still needs to be pursued, but I think we are there," says Paulson.
A signal for Asian trade
The global financial crisis has a significant impact on falling stock markets.
According to Democratic Senator Harry Reid, lawmakers are trying to get Congress to reach a final deal as early as Sunday.
They want to calm investors before trading begins on Asian financial markets, which are located in the first time zone, where the congressional decision could affect Monday’s trades.
At the moment, however, it is impossible to say for certain when the two Houses of Congress will proceed with the vote, or if the negotiations are not likely to be blocked at the last moment by this or that problem.
Legislators hope that it will be adopted in the coming days.
However, the law will still undergo many changes.
The total amount allocated to support the system should be divided into two parts.
The first $350 billion, as President George Bush wanted, must be made available as soon as possible.
But if Congress gets the impression that the program is not fulfilling its function, it has the possibility of blocking the grant of the remaining amount, following two steps: first an additional $100 billion, and then, finally, $350 billion.
Mr. Bush welcomes progress in negotiations
Although the president may veto this decision, Congress has the option of making it a minority.
Despite these changes, the main idea of the program, which was to get finances for the purchase of bad real estate titles, whose value fell, because hundreds of thousands of Americans are not able to pay their mortgages, was maintained.
“All the work is done.
The House of Representatives should be able to vote on the bill on Sunday, and the Senate on Monday," Republican Senator Judd Gregg said.
US President George Bush himself is pleased with the progress in the negotiations.
His spokesman Tony Fratto said Bush was pleased with the progress made on Saturday and appreciated "the bipartisan effort to stabilize our financial markets and protect our economy."
Limitation of golden parachutes
Senate Banking Committee Chairman Christopher Dodd, chief negotiator, says lawmakers have agreed on the responsibility of the financial program, the protection of taxpayers from losses, the relief agreement, the progress of the plan on the axis of time.
The new law also provides for the limitation of such golden parachutes for directors of companies participating in the program and establishes a committee, which will oversee the fund.
The latter should be managed by the Ministry of Finance.
“We’ve worked very hard on the issue and made significant progress toward a deal that will work and be effective for the market and for all Americans,” Paulson said.
The plan also provides for help for real estate owners, who have problems paying.
The government should negotiate new advances for mortgages it will buy back, while reducing the monthly payments of debtors and allowing them to keep their homes.
Marek: Psychological help
According to Patria Finance chief economist David Marek, the proposed plan is a good idea, but its implementation will be very difficult.
“And this is due to the fact that we don’t know what the mechanism and price will be for the repurchase of problem assets.
This point will be decisive in deciding on the share of losses between the financial sector and the government," Marek told iHNed.cz server this week.
Whether the plan will be adopted now, or early next week, is not, according to Marek, as important as that.
“It is far more important that Congressmen agree this week that they support this plan and that we dedicate it as soon as possible.
This psychological significance of the agreement, providing for the adoption of the plan, matters most at this time," Marek stressed.
A fight pushed to the extreme: MP3 players against mobiles.
We will advise you, how to choose
While virtually all mobiles can play MP3 files, no MP3 player can call.
It seems clear that it is better to buy only one phone.
However, there are enough reasons to get an independent reader.
The choice depends entirely on the mode of use and the requirements of the future owner.
It would be absurd to buy for the house an expensive high-end gramophone to put the new album of Maxim Turbulenc.
On the one hand, such musical products do not come out on vinyl, and, from the point of view of quality, there is no objective reason for this to happen.
Now, if there are stacked vinyl records in your shelves, with art rock, jazz or blues, you probably dream of such a gramophone.
The same goes for music on the move, i.e. compressed music, to put it simply - music in MP3.
There are also categories based on price and quality.
For one, it may be unacceptable to spend eight thousand crowns for a reader, in the same way that a Pink Floyd fan would have a hard time supporting earphones bought for twenty crowns at the market.
These are two extremes, between which there is enough room for everyone.
The choice is wide.
The battery life is also crucial.
Some high-end music players are capable of much more than just playing music, but these are features that are, of course, unknown to most mobile devices.
No device today is as universal as the phone.
Besides the primary functions, telephone calls and sending SMS, it is able to read music and movies, record them, it has a camera of variable quality and can, for example, even be used for navigation.
And if we take Smartphones and communicators into account, you will have a small computer in your pocket.
Since no refrigerator can grill meat and no TV will take pictures, we are practically witnessing a miracle.
However, the universal character of the mobile is not without drawbacks.
The larger the number of functions you use, the shorter the interval between reloads.
And music reading is one of the most important energy streams.
There are few mobile phones that are able to play music for ten to twelve hours, in most cases this figure is significantly lower.
In this regard, music players (especially the most rudimentary) are significantly more efficient.
In the case of cheap mobile phones, expect that they will only play music for a few hours.
If, in addition, you happen to call from time to time, get, to be sure, a second recharge for work - this is valid even for more expensive devices.
The problem will not arise for MP3 players, which are capable, following a reload, of continuous operation of at least 9 hours, including the least performing.
Another problem occurs when recording music in the mobile.
Unfortunately, a limited part of the devices has a universal USB connector, especially since not all can be directly connected to the computer, without special software.
Music can, of course, be recorded directly on the memory card, but few card readers know how to do it without reduction, given the tiny dimensions of the memory cards used in mobile phones.
As far as drives are concerned, you do not need, except for iPod, any software.
Simply fill, through the USB connector, the music device from the computer.
Most mobile phones and readers will themselves create a media library classified according to the name of the performer, the title of the album, the style, or according to the judgment of the user.
Some devices only display an index with a tree structure, similar to the Windows Explorer, others are capable of both (iriver, Samsung, Sony, Cowon, smartphones with operating system).
Readers are easier to manipulate, mobiles have more know-how
When choosing a concrete device, be especially interested in the battery life, memory capacity, quality and type of sound output and, of course, ease of control.
If the music is for you, basically, a background noise and if in the day you are going to listen to it that for a limited time, for example taking the tram, you just need any mobile reading the MP3s.
Virtually all mobile phones are capable of this today.
You don’t even have to pay too much attention to the music formats that the mobile or player is able to play.
All get to play the MP3s and the vast majority of the music that will reach you will have just this format.
It is one of the most common formats and apart from it, the vast majority of devices can also play music in WMA format.
The AAC (format used by Apple and its iPods), on the other hand, is less common.
High-end mobile phones also allow, for example, the purchase of music online.
All you need to do is to visit the corresponding operator's (or other provider's) web pages from your mobile phone and purchase the song or album in question.
This service alone should be a compelling reason to purchase a musical mobile.
The offer of the operators is unfortunately miserable and it is limited, in most cases, to radio tubes quickly made.
The prices are not the lowest either.
Nevertheless, it is generally considered that this way of buying music (whether via GSM, internet, or even wireless internet) will dominate the music industry in the future.
Most people always carry their mobile on themselves.
Every time you want to listen to something, you just have to take the mobile out of your pocket, while you have forgotten your MP3 player at home.
However, it is also important if you still have headphones or a handsfree with connection.
If not, you can use the built-in speakers, which have virtually all mobiles, but a minimum of MP3 players.
For many, the main advantage of musical mobiles is their price.
The cheapest ones normally cost less than three thousand.
For a price of three and four thousand crowns, one can have a walkman already very suitable.
However, in most cases, you will be limited by the lack of output for ordinary headphones.
The price of the best phones and the best equipped, also equipped with an input for ordinary headphones, does not exceed fifteen thousand.
Readers, on the other hand, have the advantage of having an easy command.
Really anyone manages to ensure the command of the most rudimentary readers - which do not necessarily correspond to the cheapest (see our choice).
A minimum of functions; and the resemblance of the command to that of a cassette station, commonly used in the past, or a gramophone, is obvious.
There is no risk of collision in the form of a mobile internet connected by chance, followed by a huge data transmission bill.
Which device to choose
Even the cheapest mobile phones (e.g. Vodafone 527) usually have a slot for exchangeable memory cards (M2 type, microSD, and so on).
Even taking into account the additional purchase of such a card, you will not exceed two thousand crowns.
But be careful.
Basic models only support cards with a maximum capacity of 2 GB.
Only the most expensive come out even with 8GB memory cards.
If you already own a mobile and still want to buy a cheap MP3 player, take a Cowon, a Creative, a Sony, a Samsung, an Emgeton, or an iriver.
Depending on the capacity (max. 2 GB), you should not spend more than 1,100 crowns.
If you are one of the more demanding listeners, choose specialized mobile walkmans (Sony Ericsson, some Nokia and Samsung).
These devices are equipped with independent control keys for MP3, and this is how the ease of control is close to that of an independent MP3 player.
Sony Ericsson, whose mobiles in the walkman series have the same user menu as MP3 players sold separately, is the one that has gone the farthest in this area.
The same service, in the same price category, but with a memory capacity (up to 16 GB) and a longer battery life (usually 15 hours, up to 35 hours), is provided by an MP3 player produced by one of the brands mentioned above.
A first virtual operator will win the Czech Republic this year.
Possibly.
The mobile market in Czech Republic is relatively advanced, with our operators offering virtually the same services as their partners in Western Europe.
Despite this, we still lack something - a virtual operator, which would force conventional operators to lower prices.
It may not be missing for a long time.
We have already mentioned on Mobil.cz the fact that Czech operators are among the most expensive in Europe.
The <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A> (Czech Telecommunications Office), which reported that the price of an SMS was higher in our country than in the rest of the Union, confirmed this.
Thus, following the European Commission's latest steps in the field of the regulation of roaming charges, a paradoxical situation is likely to occur - SMS sent from abroad will be for some customers of Czech mobile operators cheaper than at home.
How is it possible that prices in Czech Republic remain so high, compared to Europe?
The answer is simple, there is a lack of competition that would really like to get into the fight.
This may seem paradoxical, given that we still have three mobile networks and a penetration that far exceeds 100%.
On the contrary, mobile operators like to complain that the Czech market is extremely competitive.
In this regard, Pavel Dvo<0xC5><0x99><0xC3><0xA1>k, the President of the Council of the Czech Telecommunications Office (<0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>), who has repeatedly said that in Czech Republic there is no room for another operator, choruses with the operators.
It is probably true that a conventional operator with its own network apparently does not have much luck (in fact, now it would find frequencies only difficult).
However, there is still a possibility - a virtual operator.
It was precisely the entry of virtual operators into the mobile market that led to a considerable drop in prices, to which the traditional operators had to react.
However, even before the introduction of partying problems such as Tesco Mobile or Virgin Mobile, voices similar to those we hear today were heard in Great Britain.
However, it turned out that there was still room for such operators and that they could have a real success.
We do not have to go too far to find examples.
In February we informed you about the launch in Poland of the virtual operator Mobilking.
In just six months, this operator managed to gain more than 100,000 customers and become the fifth operator in the country.
Let’s add that behind Mobilking is the financial group Penta, which among other things owns the U:fon in Czechia.
The advantage of virtual operators is the ability to focus on a much more concrete target group.
For their operation to be efficient, they need much fewer customers than a conventional operator.
They are, in fact, exempt from the relatively high costs of construction, operation and maintenance of the mobile network.
This is how in the world, virtual operators are emerging as low-cost operators - they offer cheap calls and SMS, which is often counterbalanced by a limited service offering.
For example, Tesco Mobile offers SMS in Britain at least twice as cheap as its competitors.
However, as the example of Mobilking in Poland shows, betting on an unusual target group can also be a good publicity stunt.
Indeed, this operator specifically targets men.
"Real men choose Mobilking - an operator they like and can trust," says David Seibert, the CEO of Mobile Entertainment Company, operating this virtual operator.
It is difficult to say, if such a concept would be likely to work in our country as well.
Vodafone spokesman Miroslav <0xC4><0x8C>epick<0xC3><0xBD> said: "The Czech market is relatively small for a segmental approach, on which most virtual operators are based.
Especially since it is relatively saturated from the point of view of the offer of services."
In Czech Republic, no chance, say mobile operators
It seems nevertheless almost certain that if there will be a virtual operator in Czechia, it will not be Mobilking.
"We are discussing the expansion of this successful project, but in the Czech Republic the negotiations are not very encouraging.
The launch of Mobilking will instead take place in other countries in our area," said Jana Studni<0xC4><0x8D>kov<0xC3><0xA1>, spokesman for the financial group Penta, in a telephone interview for Mobil.cz.
It thus indirectly confirmed that the operators in the Czech Republic were, in any event, not in favour of this idea.
On the contrary, they try to do everything possible so that a potential competitor can not appear.
The GTS Novera group, which would like to take a new step in order to become a real competitor of Telefonika in the field of corporate customers, has not hidden, for a long time, its intention to launch a virtual mobile operator.
“We are very keen to be able to offer our customers not only fixed, but also mobile telecommunications services.
And the sooner the better.
We have already conducted negotiations on this possibility on several occasions with all Czech mobile operators.
With some, we have managed to move forward in the negotiations,” said group spokesman Pavel Kaidl.
So the future may be promising.
According to unofficial information, it looks like we might be able to host the first virtual operator already by the end of the year.
But for now, his creation is accompanied by total silence.
“At the moment, we do not believe that there is room in the Czech market for a virtual operator as such.
The Czech market is in comparison with others very specific.
At the moment, no subject with a complex and serious project in this area has contacted us," Vlastimil Sr<0xC5><0xA1>e<0xC5><0x88> of the Press Department of Telefonika O2 said in his statement to Mobil.cz.
Other operators also refer to the specificity of the Czech market.
T-Mobile spokeswoman Martina Kemrov<0xC3><0xA1> says in a rare agreement with O2's statement: "We have not yet registered a viable and bilaterally advantageous project, which could serve as a basis."
“It is virtually excluded that a virtual operator will appear in the T-Mobile network by the end of the year.
In order to operate in such a limited period of time, we should now have a concrete agreement.”
Vodafone instead directs its attention to fulfilling requests to obtain its own 3G license.
Miroslav <0xC4><0x8C>epick<0xC3><0xBD> says in relation to this: "We are open to negotiations with potential virtual operators, and especially in the area of shared fees and infrastructure.
This, in our opinion, means the most input from the customer’s point of view.
Vodafone’s core strategy in this area is to discover a partner to set up a common network for fast mobile internet.”
Responsible authorities: in line with operators
The approach of mobile operators is easily understandable, the entry of another operator would mean an increase in competition, would have led to lower prices and therefore a decrease in their profit.
What is the point of facilitating the advent of such a competitor?
When it comes to their interests, the operators know how to understand each other as thieves at fairs. The chicane accompanying the creation of the U:fon also bears witness to this.
The greatest apparent pressure on the <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>, when the U:fon was created, was that exerted by the company T-Mobile.
This is evidenced by publicly available information from the <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A> web pages.
Now, today, the U:fon lends itself as an argument for not accepting a virtual operator.
Martina Kemrov<0xC3><0xA1> noted: "Competition in the mobile market has also recently been amplified by the entry into the market of a fourth mobile operator.
Given the nature of the mobile market in RT, it is obvious that the entry of an additional player would subject him, and especially his services, to high demands."
But given the attitude of the mobile operators here, the indifference of the Czech regulatory bodies seems disconcerting.
However, it is not only the attitude of <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>, which, unlike Great Britain and other developed countries, unfortunately does not have the power to intervene in economic competition in the Czech Republic.
It belongs exclusively to the Office for the Protection of Economic Competition (<0xC3><0x9A>OHS).
However, the latter adopted, in the face of this problematic, its typical position.
"The entry of a virtual operator into the mobile market would be possible following the conclusion of an agreement between a mobile operator and the virtual operator in question regarding the leasing of the necessary infrastructure.
No agreement of this kind has been reached at this time, because the offer of potential interested parties has not a priori presented enough interest for conventional operators," Kristi<0xC3><0xA1>n Chalupa of the Department of External Relations of the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS said in response to our question.
A statement made in this way would not come as a surprise by representatives of the operators.
But on the part of an office, which must represent the interests of consumers and, among other things, also take care that no one takes advantage of its position in the market, such a statement is more than confusing.
Kristi<0xC3><0xA1>n Chalupa adds: "Abroad, where virtual operators are normally present, it can be seen that their entry into the market has contributed to lower prices of mobile phone services."
However, pushing for an honest functioning of the market and lowering prices is apparently not in the interests of <0xC3><0x9A>OHS.
What is actually shocking is the almost touching concord of the three mobile operators, which stems from their reactions.
The question, if this is really a coincidence, arises quite naturally.
In the same way, a price of gasoline strictly identical to all petrol stations is probably due to chance and the hard fight of competition.
"The Office has not found any signs of anti-competitive behaviour in this regard, so it has no reason to intervene in any way.
None of the operators has a dominant position, and therefore no operator has an increased corresponding responsibility for its market behaviour.
The tools needed to open up the mobile market to virtual operators are likely to be lacking even in the telecoms regulator," Chaloupa said in his statement.
One of the many points of disagreement is the interpretation of the dominant market position.
Of course, there is an analysis of the relevant markets carried out by the <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>, according to which telecommunications constitute, from the point of view of economic competition, a single market.
None of the Czech operators has a dominant position on such a market.
However, some legal experts propose a different view of things: in order for the creation of a virtual operator to be possible, it is necessary to obtain, each time, the consent of the network operator.
And the mobile operator quite logically has a monopoly on its network.
This is how it necessarily plays a dominant role in a certain segment of its activity.
However, even without admitting this argument, it should be at least worrying for the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS that three mobile operators are visibly proceeding in a similar manner.
However, the complaints of many interested parties (including the company GTS Novera, already mentioned) show that they face similar constraints in the negotiations with all operators.
Putting responsibility back on the <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A> is a fairly common trick in communications, by means of which the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS washes the hands of the case.
We have already encountered this type of attitude in several similar cases.
Unfortunately, it has not been possible to extend the <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>'s powers in the field of economic competition in telecommunications in the newly adopted Telecommunications Act, although many experts have promised to improve the situation.
This, the representatives of the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS must know very well, but their interests seem to lie elsewhere.
When no one looks, it can work
That said, the operation of a kind of pseudo-virtual operators, several in Czech mobile networks, remains unnoticed.
These are companies publishing their own price lists for mobile telephone services, but these are only partly public.
In most cases, it is about companies dealing with multi-level marketing.
Personalized mobile phone services are offered by Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and many others.
The price lists of these firms usually reach only elected officials.
The trick consists in the fact that the company makes in front of the operator figure of a classic business customer, who orders a large amount of SIM cards.
As an important customer, she gets special price offers (and others).
The problem is that the commercial conditions of all Czech mobile operators prohibit such resale.
"If what you're talking about happens, it could be a breach of the contractual terms that we would consider and that could result in a termination of the collaboration with the company in question," Martina Kemrov<0xC3><0xA1> said in a statement.
Nevertheless, it is rather unlikely that an echo of such activity has not reached the heads of mobile operators.
In particular, in the case of the three companies mentioned, there may be thousands of customers.
No operator, however, is against such a procedure.
Indeed, the activities of these firms bring them not-negligible benefits, and at the same time, as opposed to real virtual operators, they do not threaten them with their own official marketing.
Miroslav <0xC4><0x8C>epick<0xC3><0xBD> points out the possible problems: "The law allows such speculation, however, the services of these companies are only used by a negligible percentage of customers.
In addition, they are forced to admit that the SIM card in their phone is not registered under their name, so they cannot fully dispose of it, in the manner of ordinary customers of mobile operators.
But this is precisely what should seem strange to <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>.
In addition, another question arises at <0xC3><0x9A>OHS.
If mobile operators turn a blind eye to such a procedure, why are they blocking the creation of a virtual operator?
It should be added that the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS has relatively broad powers to reveal such an activity, and although it will not wish to be satisfied with the explanations of the operators, who claim to have no idea that this would happen, their contractual conditions prohibit it.
When we are no longer the most expensive country
As we have already mentioned on several occasions, the entry of virtual operators into the mobile market has led to a considerable decrease in the price of services.
However, in virtually all countries where virtual operators appeared, the conventional operators tried sometimes more, sometimes less, to prevent their creation.
The arguments used by the latter were practically the same - a market too small, even too saturated, problems with the quality of services, etc.
However, it is precisely at this level that regulatory bodies have intervened in developed countries, defending not the interests of mobile operators, but those of their customers.
Both through formal measures and informal pressure, they ended up with the creation of a first virtual operator, followed by others.
Unfortunately, Czech regulators are treating this issue like a hot potato that you get rid of by passing it on to a nearby target.
Following the experiences we have, we cannot get rid of the impression that confusion in skills is in these cases more than beneficial to them.
But let's not throw the sleeve after the hit.
If the behind-the-scenes information is true and a virtual operator will soon appear at our site, the Czech mobile market may be on the move again.
If one of the operators has accepted the creation of a virtual mobile operator, the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS will hardly be able to remain impassive in the face of the rejection (discrimination) of other interested parties.
And perhaps we will stop calling more expensive than in the rest of Europe.
The new Czech anthem has four new versions.
Choose the best
Listen to the four achievements of the new version of the Czech national anthem.
On Sunday, on the occasion of Czech Nationality Day, Prime Minister Mirek Topol<0xC3><0xA1>nek solemnly presented the new recordings of the national anthem Kde domov m<0xC5><0xAF>j (Where is my homeland?).
The anthem was again recorded by the National Theatre Orchestra under the direction of Ji<0xC5><0x99><0xC3><0xAD> B<0xC4><0x9B>lohl<0xC3><0xA1>vek.
We have four versions - with a solo male or female song, an interpretation with chorus and an instrumental version.
The song is performed by Kate<0xC5><0x99>ina Kn<0xC4><0x9B><0xC5><0xBE><0xC3><0xAD>nkov<0xC3><0xA1> and Adam Plachetka.
Otakar Jeremi<0xC3><0xA1><0xC5><0xA1> and Jaroslav Kr<0xC4><0x8D>ek are the authors of the arrangements of the anthem.
You can listen to the four new versions on the iHNed.cz server.
B<0xC4><0x9B>lohl<0xC3><0xA1>vek considers Czech national song as one of the most beautiful hymns.
As he had previously entrusted to <0xC4><0x8C>esk<0xC3><0xBD> rozhlas (the Czech public radio), he chose for the interpretation of solo versions of singers with young and representative voices, which are marked and appreciated.
