Sudetenland demanded a referendum in the US
The Sudeten Germans demanded in 1945 that <0xC5><0xA0>umava be integrated into the United States.
This stems from a letter deposited in the collections of the Jiho<0xC4><0x8D>esk<0xC3><0xA1> v<0xC4><0x9B>deck<0xC3><0xA1> knihovna (The Scientific Library of Southern Bohemia).
If we cannot be part of Germany or Austria, we at least want to live under the patronage of the United States of America.
In 1945, some groups of Sudeten Germans allegedly addressed the President of the United States with such a desire.
This stems among other things from a letter preserved in a private archive, which is now deposited in the collections of the Jiho<0xC4><0x8D>esk<0xC3><0xA1> v<0xC4><0x9B>deck<0xC3><0xA1> knihovna.
Germans from <0xC4><0x8C>esk<0xC3><0xBD> Krumlov in the letter begged the US president not to allow "<0xC5><0xA1>umavsk<0xC3><0xA1> <0xC5><0xBE>upa" (forest region south of Bohemia) - annexed by Hitler under the Munich agreement - to be returned to Czechoslovakia.
"We have understood the situation well and want to be sure that the words proclaiming that American troops come to German territory not as oppressors and enemies, but as liberators," is written in the letter, signed "People, to whom the fate of the <0xC5><0xA0>umava cares."
Given that the rallies to Czechoslovakia are allegedly promising - knowing the Czech national character - only of brutality, disrespectful attitude, misunderstanding, oppression and servitude, the authors of the letter ask the American president to take in his hands the protectorate of <0xC5><0xA0>umava for now and forever.
"We cannot believe that you would grant this territory to a state foreign to us, which oppresses and destroys minorities and which has not contributed in any way to the victory of the Allies without taking into account the opinion of a quarter of a million inhabitants," the letter read.
The alleged reason why the authors cannot sign the letter is the fear of the desire for revenge of the "Czech oppressors".
If the president of the United States doubted the opinion of the Germans of <0xC5><0xA0>umava, he would only have to organize, according to the authors of the letter, a referendum in the region to establish whether its inhabitants wanted to be part of the United States, or to live under the patronage of the United States.
Although the text contained in the letter may, given current knowledge of post-war history, seem somewhat naive, according to some survivors, it illustrates well the expectations of the Sudeten Germans of the time.
While the Czech Germans had at least to foresee that the question of their expulsion from the republic would arise, very few of them admitted to such a possibility.
Some expected that the United States and Great Britain would obtain some kind of autonomy for the Sudetenland.
Others believed they would simply stay in Czechoslovakia.
The famous Austrian journalist Gustav Chalupa, born in <0xC4><0x8C>eské Bud<0xC4><0x9B>jovice, confirms this.
During the war, he was, as a German of <0xC4><0x8C>eské Bud<0xC4><0x9B>jovice, engaged in the navy in the Baltic countries.
When at the end of the war he was captured by the English and placed in the Holstein region's capture camp, dozens of Czech Germans came to consult him for him to teach them Czech.
“They believed that once they got home, the Czech would benefit them,” Chalupa said.
None of the captured Germans who lived in Czechoslovakia before the war believed that, following the Bene<0xC5><0xA1> Decrees, he would be expelled from the republic.
