Olmert would return almost all the occupied territories in exchange for peace
Ehud Olmert, the president of the Israeli Provisional Government, called for the restitution of virtually all the territories occupied in 1967, including the West Bank, East Jerusalem and the Golan Heights, in exchange for peace with Palestine and Syria.
He made the statement in an interview published Monday by the daily Yedioth Ahronoth.
“We need to reach an agreement with the Palestinians, which means that it will be necessary to return almost all (occupied) territories, if not all,” Olmert told the daily.
"We will keep a certain percentage of the territory, but we will have to cede to the Palestinians a similar percentage (of Israeli territory), since without it, peace will not be made," he added.
He admitted that the possible restitution would include East Jerusalem.
"He who desires security in Jerusalem, and especially does not want tractors and bulldozers to crush his feet, as happened to one of my best friends, will have to give up parts of Jerusalem," Olmert remarked, referring to the two attacks in the city in July, in which several people were killed and dozens injured.
According to the prime minister, it will be necessary to find "a special solution for the Temple Mount, the sacred and historical places" located inside the Old City.
“Anyone who wants to maintain Israeli sovereignty over the entire city will be forced to integrate 270,000 Arabs.
It won't work," he later pointed out.
Retirement from the Golan Heights
Olmert also supported Israel's withdrawal from the Golan Heights, which he said was a prerequisite for a peace agreement with Syria.
But this would also require some effort on the part of Damascus.
"I do not propose to conclude peace with Syria solely on the basis of a Golan retreat," he said.
“The Syrians know very well what they will have to give up to get the Golan.
They will have to renounce their current relations with Iran; they will have to renounce their relationship with Hezbollah (Shiite movement); they will have to renounce the constant support they give to the terrorism of Hamas (Shiite movement), Al-Kaida (terrorist network), as well as that of jihad (holy war) in Iraq.
Questions that arise after the accident: Are the stewards in the bus illegal?
The law ignores them; walking in a long-distance car is forbidden
In the context of the tragic accident of the Student Agency bus near Padua, Italy, the question arises whether stewards and passengers can move inside the bus during the journey.
"If we want to strictly and formally comply with the law, the activity of a steward is contrary to the law on road traffic," said transport ministry spokesman Karel Hanzelka.
The accident in question, during which a 22-year-old hostess was killed, was apparently caused by the driver of a truck that crossed the path of the coach.
The girl was unfortunately sitting next to the driver on the most dangerous seat of the vehicle, although she had two other seats at her disposal.
However, the bus can have an accident, or even brake abruptly, also when the steward serves the coffee or distributes the newspapers.
What matters is whether the coach is under its technical data sheet equipped with standing places or not.
If this standing equipment is not approved, passengers must remain seated.
The Student Agency long-distance coaches do not have standing spaces; this has been confirmed to Aktu<0xC3><0xA1>ln<0xC4><0x9B>.cz by the director of the company Radim Jan<0xC4><0x8D>ura.
"This is an issue that we have discussed with the ministry and, at first, it prohibits any movement of passengers.
Then they canceled it and we got passengers to go to the toilet during the trip provided they had their own seat," he said.
The law ignores the steward.
"There is no unambiguous legal interpretation of the role of steward - no legal prescriptions deal with this role.
On the other hand, there is also no legal requirement prohibiting the carrier from offering services.
The road transport law only knows the term vehicle receiver; it does not define its rights and duties," added Spokesperson Hanzelka more ambiguly.
Josef Pokorn<0xC3><0xBD>, the director of the road traffic department, believes, on the contrary, that the law sufficiently addresses the problem.
"It all depends on whether the coach has in its homologation the permission to offer standing places.
It’s all in there,” he said.
Coaches are divided into urban, where there are standing places and a limited maximum speed, long-distance with standing places and a higher allowed speed, and long-distance buses without standing places with the highest allowed maximum speed and seats equipped with seat belts.
As in the plane, says an expert
Jaroslav Ho<0xC5><0x99><0xC3><0xAD>n, an expert at BESIP (road traffic safety) in transport safety, does not see the movement of stewards on board as a major problem.
"In regular traffic, there is no danger. The situation can be compared to that of service in planes.
There, too, he is not sure when turbulence will occur and the flight attendant may bump her head.”
"In the event that the bus braked abruptly, the laws of physics would obviously be valid.
In the same way as in an urban bus or in a tram.
The carrier must manage the safety of the stewards through internal prescriptions," he says and also believes that from the point of view of the law, the issue is not resolved.
Jan<0xC4><0x8D>ura is ready to remove these services
The Student Agency is the only bus carrier to offer the services of stewards.
He hires two hundred.
Even after this accident, the director does not consider their trade to be a risky trade.
“However, as soon as I feel like it’s a risky job, I’ll remove it.
Passengers can receive their coffee and newspaper upon boarding.
It would also reduce costs,” he says.
The safety concern is the reason given to the absence of stewards in his vehicles the director of the Asiana Alexei Litvine, which ensures, in comparison with SA, a very small number of lines.
"We don't have hostesses. We have been opposed to this from the beginning.
Sooner or later it will end in a fatal accident," he told T<0xC3><0xBD>den.cz a year ago.
A Great Tragedy Has Arrived
A young hostess from the region of Plze<0xC5><0x88>, who had been working for the company for two years, was killed in the accident on the Naples line.
A Slovenian truck probably left the emergency stop strip without using a flashing light and blocked the way to the bus.
The driver of the latter tried to avoid it by means of a sudden maneuver, but he approached it from his right side.
Jan<0xC4><0x8D>ura refuses that the two seats reserved for the stewards’ rest were sold.
"In the case of long-distance lines, it is not possible to reserve these seats, they are blocked."
The company plans to file a complaint against the truck driver.
For the compensation of the family of the girl, the agency will not wait for the judgment of the court, but with regard to financial compensation, it also relies on the culprit.
An amendment to the law?
Not in sight
An amendment to the law, which has been in the works for more than a year, by a group of 30 experts from the Ministry of Transport, could provide clarification on the movements of stewards on board the coach.
"It has not come to any conclusions on this point.
In fact, she is not too interested in buses, but rather in the point system, the maximum speed on the highway and the use of the mobile phone at the wheel," says expert Ho<0xC5><0x99><0xC3><0xAD>n.
"The Ministry of Transport does not consider the activity of the stewards as something that would fundamentally jeopardize the safety of passengers," said spokesman Hanzelka, adding that the control of the safety of buses is under the power of the police and the Office for Safety at Work.
The hopes of the Düsseldorfers rest on Frankfurt.
The key words were not lacking in the letter sent by the WestLB Steering Committee to the employees of the house.
By a union of the entities of the Düsseldorf financial institution with the Frankfurt Deka-Bank, "the central institution of the financial markets of the financial group of the Sparkasse" could be constituted, according to the letter made public on Monday.
