Nights of insomnia for the shareholders of Hypo Real Estate
The German banking system is relatively stable, insisted the Federal Finance Minister only a few weeks ago.
What a chance that the politician used the word "relatively" and that he slipped that the German banking sector would not be spared from the crisis movements.
This actually happened this weekend.
The Bavarian real estate financier Hypo Real Estate (HRE), on the side of the DAX, obtains from a consortium of German banks a loan of one billion to protect itself from the turbulence of the markets.
A person in the confidence of the situation told Reuters on Monday that the aid credits are issued up to an amount of 35 billion euros.
The Hypo Real Estate should now pay interest on the fraction to which it would thus be entitled.
The money comes from both private and public banks.
In the background, it is the daughter company Depfa that bears the losses.
The state financier had, according to a newspaper article, refinanced himself in the very short term for long-term projects for which he had borrowed money - which is no longer possible because of mistrust of the markets.
In the first half of 2008, the bank's liquidity reserve had been reduced by 95 percent to 2.37 million euros, the equity rate also had slightly weakened from 1.6 to 1.45 percent.
On-going and net profits from financial transactions were down to zero compared to the same period a year earlier, profits from the allocation of fixed receivables and securities as well as the termination of provisions in credit operations had fallen by more than 70 per cent to €5 million.
And it was only thanks to the significant profits from the repayment of downstream accounting costs from the restructuring of the former Depfa group, as well as the book interest repayment of tax procedures and commercial purchases for Konzern companies that the earnings deficit of about 16 percent proved to be moderate.
After his privatization in 1990, the former state financier had initially speculated poorly on industrial real estate loans, which had then been subordinated to Aareal Bank.
Because conventional state financing was not profitable enough, Depfa then engaged more intensively in infrastructure projects and in the financing of joint projects between private investors and the state (Private-Public-Partnership, PPP) and diversified internationally.
On the value of the daughter company, the Hypo Real Estate must depreciate which should have an essential material effect on the calculation of the group's gains and losses, which still remains rather vague.
The fact is that the dividends have been amputated.
By 2007, they had already been cut by two-thirds.
Since the acquisition of Depfa, Hypo Real Estate has been a highly important state and infrastructure investor.
It is stronger than other refinancing-dependent institutions in the inter-bank market since it has no client deposits.
With the bankruptcy of the investment bank Lehman Brothers two weeks ago, the allocation of loans between banks has again considerably stagnated, with the banks accumulating their liquidity.
The Hypo Real Estate needs annually for a part - about 50 billion euros - of all the credits of the Depfa of a short-term means of refinancing.
According to a statement from Hypo Real Estate, the group's financing need is covered by medium-term credit and the company is protected from the influence of international financial markets largely out of business at present.
Other sources say refinancing would be secured through the funds until the end of 2009.
HRE Chairman Georg Funke, however, explained that the Hypo Real Estate group should no longer have to resort to financial markets in the medium term.
The Federal Bank and the Federal Institution for the Supervision of Financial Services (Bafin) assume that the capacity of the Hypo Real Group in the market is now assured.
The bank’s shareholders and creditors can only hope for this.
However, given the dynamics and imponderability of the crisis, there is no certainty.
Moreover, it is not unthinkable that funding should not be used in its entirety.
But neither can the opposite be ruled out.
After the bank is, according to the latest press releases, still on the doorstep of insolvency Sunday evening, this rescue, at least provisional, will not succeed in reassuring the minds either.
The share price fell 75 percent to 3.30 euros.
Bond prices, on the other hand, are doing particularly well.
While debt in the first place has barely moved, the prices of second-rate loans are declining.
Most affected are the investment funds of the former daughter company Württemberg Hypo and those, of course, which have a lifespan beyond 2009.
The bonds of Hypo Real Estate Bank previously seemed to be an alternative speculation investment, now their value must be considered dependent on the stability of the international banking system after the net hardening of the banking crisis and the crisis of the institute itself that brought the crisis into the establishment through the purchase of Depfa Bank.
As long as the issuing institutes, governments and less affected commercial banks are still ready to support the system, we can assume a reversal of arrears in time.
Or something will happen that no one dares to hope for right now – that the financial crisis can be overcome in the next 15 months.
But in the face of the renewed noises of partial nationalization, the probability that approached security has now become a mere well-founded hope.
This should reserve nights of insomnia above all for long-term creditors on the decision whether they should part with their commitments.
Short-term investors can still use what they drew a line from to defer losses for the next few years on the next capital income tax on stock market gains automatically levied.
