Rats have feelings too.
A rat or a cockroach flees in the face of danger, does that mean he also feels fear?
Neurophysicist Joseph LeDoux is convinced of this: many animals also have sensations.
But how can we verify that he experiences the same thing when he behaves in the same way as we do?
In the online magazine "Edge", contributions have been published for several years by famous scientists.
SPIEGEL ONLINE presents in a series of articles answers to the question "What do you think is true without being able to prove it?"
I believe that animals have sensations and other states of consciousness without me or anyone else having so far been able to prove it just as one cannot prove that other human beings have consciousness.
But in this case, we can at least hope that all human brains have the same configuration.
As soon as we turn to other species and address the questions of feeling or consciousness in general, we enter into difficult practicable terrain because the Hardware does not match.
When a rat is in danger, it does the same thing as many other animals: it dies, flees, or attacks.
Human beings behave in the same way, which is why some scientists deduce a comparable subjective experience.
However, I do not believe it.
Two aspects of the structure of the brain make transposition of our subjective experience to that of animals difficult.
One aspect is that the circuits almost always associated with human consciousness include the prefrontal lateral cortex (due to its participation in short-term memory and in the functions of direction and execution).
This vast region is much more developed in humans than in other primates and appears to be entirely absent in other beings.
At the very least, therefore, for those aspects of our consciousness that depend on the prefrontal cortex, including the consciousness of who we are, and the ability to predict and decide, it is reasonable to assume that the human being differs even from other primates.
Another significant peculiarity could lie in the linguistic nature of Man: much of his existence being related to language, it often means that his consciousness depends on it.
In this case, animals could be excluded.
But even if consciousness were not to depend on language, it would surely influence it, so that animal consciousness, no matter how it is produced, would probably differ much from most of our states of consciousness.
This is why it is so difficult to determine what consciousness may look like in other animals.
If this, internal and subjective, does not allow itself to be measured or, because of this particular Hardware, analysed based on our own experience, then its observation poses great problems for us.
Most of my developments refer to the content of conscious experience, but there is next to it another aspect of consciousness that should be more easily accessible scientifically.
Animal consciousness processes could be examined regardless of their content, and this is exactly what happened in studies of primate short-term memory, particularly with the example of visualization.
But in this approach that Christof Koch and Francis Crick followed, we focus more on the nerve correlations of consciousness than on the causal mechanisms: the two can be identical or not.
Interestingly, this approach also highlights the weight of the prefrontal cortex in performing visualization.
But what does this mean for emotions?
I conclude that an emotional system such as fear is activated in a brain aware of its own activity.
What we refer to as “fear” is therefore the mental state in which we find ourselves when the activity of the localized defense system in the brain (or its sequels, such as the reactions of the body) seizes the living memory.
Thus observed, the emotions are closely related to the regions of the cortex that characterize primates and especially humans.
Subtle degrees of feeling, associated with our volatile nature, emerge, because we can, with the help of words and grammar, differentiate and categorize states to impute them to others other than ourselves.
In contrast, Antonio Damasio, for example, thinks that sensations from primitive activities are born in the body sensation regions of the cortex and brain stem, as does Jaak Pankseep who, however, focuses more on the brain stem.
As this network has not changed much during human evolution, it could quite participate in transversal sensations of all kinds.
From a purely theoretical point of view, I cannot contradict it, but I believe it indemonstrable.
Pankseep argues that what appears to be fear in humans and rats is likely to be felt as fear in both cases: yet how could one check whether rats and humans feel the same when they behave similarly?
A cockroach runs away from danger, but if it feels fear?
In my opinion, similar behaviors are not enough to prove identical experiences.
Certainly, the nervous comparison helps: rats and humans have similar brain trunks, but cockroaches do not even have a brain.
But is the brain stem at the origin of sensations?
And even if we could prove it to humans, how could we prove it to rats?
I think rats and other mammals, maybe even cockroaches (who knows?) have sensations.
But I don't know how to prove it.
And because their sensations are likely completely different from ours (since human consciousness relies on special circuits and language), I prefer to explore emotional behavior than rat emotional sensations.
In any case, progress is made on the nervous plane insofar as the same is measured in rats and in humans.
As I do not explore language and consciousness in rats, nor the sensations, I do not know if they exist.
This could be seen as short-term, but I prefer to move forward rather than constantly bump into a wall.
I am an emotional pragmatist.
