The German Günther Bauer mixes in "Flamenco - people" the theatricality of some stagings with singers, dancers and guitarists with this lesser known side of artists.
In this project, the photographer takes up the particular iconography of flamenco from different angles.
Included in the program of Flemish Photography Month, the exhibition "reflects the international importance of flamenco, which is growing every day", explains the creator, who clarifies that "Flamenco - people" "can be anyone but, after seeing the photos, the observer realizes that they are not typical images of artists on stage.
These people photographed "in the street" are artists able to transmit on stage passion, sadness, joy ... captivating the audience.
To capture moments of personality of these artists you do not have to take pictures on stage.
They have a personality and character of their own.
What interested me was to create an intimate atmosphere that allowed me to capture with the camera moments of personality of flamenco stars.”
With the festival "Song of the Mines", Bauer began in 1997 a long journey to photograph singers, guitarists or dancers with a plate camera.
These are portraits that, thanks to the choice of camera and material, recall classical photography.
The implementation of different stylistic means breaks with the classical side of the image, giving it a touch of modernity, this reflects the perception of flamenco according to Bauer: "A music with very traditional roots that evolves and that surprises every day".
It is not about the dance or the song itself, but about the personality and character of the artist who captivates the audience with his art.
The search for the essential and magic was the constant of this work that is presented these days at the gallery El Fot<0xC3><0xB3>mata.
Flamenco stars such as Diego El Cigala, Chano Lobato, Cristina Hoyos, Enrique Morente, El Lebrijano, Antonio Canales, Vicente Amigo, among others, are part of the selection made from about seventy photographed artists.
The project has been transformed into an anthology of flamenco, which will soon be published in a collection of portraits exhibited at the gallery.
Bauer's passion for portraits led him to repeat the idea two years ago with the "Portraits of old sportsmen" ("SportARTproject").
Although the concepts are different in "Flamenco - people", the photographer admits that he loves to photograph the portrait of people, get to know them and be able to enter their lives for a more or less long moment.
I think in photography portraiture is the hardest genre.
You find yourself in front of people, characters that you sometimes don’t know or who only give you a few minutes to take a picture of them.
Despite these circumstances, as a photographer, I always try to make my ideas come true.”
This collection of portraits of the current flamenco that is entitled "Flamenco - people", is exhibited at the Galerie El Fot<0xC3><0xB3>mata, located at number 20 of rue de la Mata (street parallel to the People of Hercules) which will be open until October 16 next.
