Recidivists of alcohol at the wheel will have to install the system 'alcolock'
The Minister of the Interior wants the driver who has had more than three administrative penalties for alcohol, to install in his vehicle a system that prevents starting the vehicle in a state of drunkenness, or if he does not blow.
The initiative was already announced in June last year and now appears in the report of the Minister of State in which this initiative is considered a pilot project that will last one year.
Its purpose is to reintegrate the driver by offering him road rehabilitation courses.
The Minister of State in charge of road safety but also the General Directorate of Road Safety and the Foundation Technological Institute for Automotive Safety will participate in this initiative.
According to statistics, between 30% and 75% of motorists arrested for driving more than once intoxicated, take the car back.
The alcoholock would avoid this since it is a system connected to the vehicle that measures the level of alcohol in the breath and prevents the vehicle from starting if the driver does not blow before; or when the driver's alcohol level is higher than the allowed.
Its cost is more than 1,000 euros and is at the expense of the driver.
In this regard, a study conducted in the United States in 2007 showed that vehicles equipped with this device reduced offences by up to 65% in the first year of installation.
And in Spain it is estimated that this could save the lives of 115 people every year.
This measure is limited to administrative sanctions for two reasons: dealing with these behaviours before they turn into criminal offences.
And facilitate its implementation, since the legal reform can be done by ordinary means but, however, the reform done by criminal means requires a reform of the organic law.
The device is not yet available on the Spanish market in any commercial form, although some industrial and functional vehicles already have one on an experimental basis.
Precisely tomorrow, the Congress of Deputies will vote on an initiative of the Spanish Socialist Party that proposes to install this system in school buses as it was done in France.
