The interview - Blood is safe again
Héma-Québec celebrated the 10th anniversary of its foundation yesterday, and its president, Dr. Francine Décary, was right to rejoice, as Héma-Québec has become one of the safest and most effective blood suppliers in the world.
And most importantly, he regained the public confidence that had been seriously shaken by the contaminated blood scandal in the 1980s and 1990s.
As is known, national blood reserves managed by the Canadian Red Cross Transfusion Service were contaminated with acquired immunodeficiency virus (HIV) and hepatitis C virus during the 1980s.
In the face of this tragedy and the grumbling of the public, in February 1994 the Government of Canada instituted a public inquiry, chaired by Justice Horace Krever, which sought to shed light on the circumstances that led to such a tragedy and to make recommendations to prevent such a disaster from happening again.
While Judge Krever was late in filing his report, some provinces set up a committee to plan a new blood management system in Canada.
In Quebec, the Gélineau committee fulfilled this mandate.
Following the Gelineau and Krever reports, two suppliers were created in Canada: Héma-Québec to serve Quebec and the Canadian Blood Services to supply all other provinces and territories.
"In 1998, when Héma-Québec began operations, barely 38% of people still had confidence in the blood system in Quebec," recalls Dr. Décary.
The situation was daunting.
Through efforts to improve the safety of blood products and work in the field in the years that followed, we regained public confidence," she said before proudly stating that at the beginning of 2008, nearly 94% of the Quebec population now had confidence in Héma-Québec.
Dr. Décary, however, keeps in mind that “trust is something extremely fragile.”
Since its inception on September 28, 1998, Héma-Québec has applied the precautionary principle.
At that time, many cases of the human form of mad cow disease, a new variant of Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, were seen in Europe, says the one that has held the fort since its foundation in 1998.
"And we didn't know at all if this disease could be transmitted through blood.
One of the main recommendations of the Krever and Gelineau reports was that when this is not known and a serious disease can result, in this case Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, which is characterized by degeneration of the brain leading inevitably to death, exclusion measures are introduced.
In April 1999, blood was denied to people who had been in the United Kingdom for more than a month since 1980.
Now, a few years ago, it was shown beyond any doubt that this disease is transmitted through the blood.
This episode showed us that the precautionary principle that was applied made sense.”
In 1999, a much more sensitive technique of HIV testing appeared on the market: nucleic acid (NAT) tests, which allow the presence of the virus itself to be directly detected in the blood of donors and not that of antibodies against the virus, on which the tests used until then were based.
The TANs shortened the mute period, which stretches from the time the person was infected to the time when the first viruses can be detected in the blood by our techniques, explains the specialist.
This period could be reduced to less than a week.
This has substantially reduced the risk of certain donors becoming infected unknowingly and not being able to be detected.
These improvements have significantly reduced the risk of contracting AIDS through a blood transfusion.
Today, one in 12 million people are at risk of receiving HIV-contaminated blood.
In other words, it means that 12 million blood products will have to be distributed before someone is infected with HIV.
As Héma-Québec distributes between 400,000 and 500,000 blood products each year, it will take more than 24 years before a case of transmission of HIV by a blood product occurs.
I believe that today we can feel comfortable receiving or prescribing a blood transfusion to recover health," says the CEO of Héma-Québec.
“Our challenge for the next decade is to maintain the safety of our products.
We never know which pathogen will emerge in the system.
Not later than last year, the Chikungunya virus appeared on the island of Réunion, which, like the West Nile virus, is transmitted by an insect in the blood.
It is necessary to be constantly vigilant," continues Dr. Décary before stressing that in addition to a safe supply, Héma-Québec must also provide a sufficient supply.
“The needs are increasing because the population is getting older.
Because cancer treatments are more aggressive, patients often need a refill of red blood cells or platelets.
The aging of the population also has an impact on the blood donor network, which on average only includes 3% of Quebecers eligible for blood donation.
Anyone who is 18 years of age or older who meets the eligibility criteria can still donate blood every 56 days, or six times a year.
On average, 14% of people who offer their blood are not accepted, because they have AIDS or malaria, for example, and if they have traveled to a country with malaria, they will be excluded for a period of one year.
“With this 3%, we are able to maintain an inventory that meets the needs of hospitals.
Shortages are very rare.
But it is necessary to renew the members of this network of donors as they age and can no longer donate their blood.
However, it is difficult to convince people to donate their blood, but above all to withhold them and encourage them to become regular donors.
Today’s life is so unbridled, we rarely find time to spend an hour giving blood,” said Francine Décary.
With an annual budget of $297 million, Héma-Québec provides not only blood products, but also human tissues, including bone grafts, heart valves, eyeballs and skin that is almost exclusively used for large burns.
These tissues are analyzed, processed and frozen before being stored at Héma-Québec, which also manages the only public cord blood bank in Quebec.
The umbilical cord, which was once considered a biomedical waste, is full of blood rich in stem cells that can be used to treat serious diseases, such as leukemia.
“A few weeks ago, we celebrated the banking of our 1,000th cord blood sample and are planning to take more than 1,000 a year.
We should start offering them for transplants early next year,” says Dr. Décary, who describes this cord blood sampling program as very popular.
"Several mothers are disappointed that they cannot access it," because Héma-Québec does not have the means to offer this complex and expensive program in all hospitals in Quebec.
