Free Opinion - Barrick Gold's Orwellian Discourse
In its September 17 edition, Le Devoir published a letter from Mr. Patrick J. Garver, Executive Vice President of Canadian Mining Barrick Gold.
Pursuing an Orwellian logic, he claims that the world's largest gold company has filed a defamation lawsuit of six million against three authors and a small publishing house without the penny in order to launch a "transparent public debate".
If it is true that judges are independent and impartial, it is not the truth that they judge, especially in the case of defamation proceedings, but the law.
Unsurprisingly, this fundamental difference is completely obscured by Mr. Garver.
For Barrick Gold, the best way to conduct a public debate would be to bring to ruin anyone who dares to support a position contrary to his own?
Regardless of the outcome of the trial, the authors and publishers of the Black Canada book will have to spend considerable sums to prepare their defense and fight, with very unequal weapons, against an army of lawyers supported by the almost bottomless pockets of the mine.
The tactic, in these unequal struggles, is often to ruin the defendants in order to impose an amicable settlement that will gag the opposition in addition to frightening anyone who dares to look at the issue again.
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public debate, it was in front of public opinion that she should have presented her vision of the facts.
Unlike in many of the countries where Barrick Gold works, debates in Canada are normally conducted through the exchange of ideas and not by batons.
So it was enough for the mine to open its books, its files and to establish a real debate, through the newspapers, the media, the publications and the funding of independent research teams that could have shed light on the issue.
But Barrick Gold does not seem to trust the public and rejects the petitions and letters of support to the authors of Black Canada.
Perhaps Mr. Garver could explain how he can both demand a "public" debate while scorning the opinions of that same public?
In the Vice-President's world, it seems that this word refers only to high-paying lawyers and not to all Canadians; this is a rather narrow view of the concept.
In a democracy, even critics have the right to speak out.
What Barrick Gold does not understand - or does not want to understand - is that the public that supports the authors and publishers of Noir Canada does so primarily because they reject the brutal way of mining.
This public is ready to hear Barrick and to judge, but on the basis of civilized exchanges of arguments, and not in the context of what many perceive as a gag prosecution (continuing the "public debate", Barrick Gold has just filed a formal notice with the authors of Black Canada urging them to stop using this term...).
Beyond Garver’s surreal discourse, the pursuit of Barrick Gold is a direct attack on the freedom of academic research and the quest for truth, essential to any democratic society.
It denies, as a whole, the right to citation from credible sources and to debate on facts and interpretations, which are the very basis of intellectual work.
If it is impossible to study and discuss topics that are displeasing to the rich businesses of this world in a country like Canada, under pain of repeated prosecution, who will be able to do so?
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public and transparent debate, she could do so by following the scientific standards used by the authors of Black Canada.
She has a right of reply.
The academic community, to which we belong, has long known how to deal with debates and disagreements and to resolve conflicts.
Barrick Gold’s disproportionate pursuit clearly shows that, contrary to what she claims, she has no desire for a transparent debate.
This is a loss for academia, as it is for public debate in Canada, and it is time for governments to put in place mechanisms to limit such abusive prosecutions.
Wall Street Rescue Operation - Democrats and Republicans agree
The Bush administration and congressional leaders, both Republicans and Democrats, finally reached an agreement yesterday on the biggest economic bailout since the Great Depression of the 1930s.
The new version of the $700 billion plan to curb the financial crisis that has rocked Wall Street for months has yet to be endorsed by both houses of Congress.
It includes: better control by the elected representatives of its implementation, new mechanisms to ensure the reimbursement of the public money committed, new provisions to contain the number of houses seized for non-payment, as well as a right to look at the salaries paid to the managers of the companies rescued.
U.S. Treasury Secretary Henry Paulson, House Speaker Nancy Pelosi, and Republican Rep. at the negotiating table, Senator Judd Gregg, announced the good news minutes after midnight yesterday at the end of a two-day negotiating marathon.
"We have made great progress towards an agreement that will be effective in the markets," Bush administration representative Henry Paulson said.
“Everything was done in a way that protected the real economy and ordinary Americans from the ongoing crisis on Wall Street,” she said.
“That’s the bottom line: if we don’t do that, the trauma, chaos and disruption to the daily lives of Americans will be immense,” Rep. Judd Gregg said.
Negotiations had turned to the sprint in recent hours for fear of the effect of a further failure on the mood of investors.
The time limit we agreed on was the opening of markets this morning.
Associated late in the negotiations, the two candidates for the US presidential election showed themselves quite supportive of the agreement, but they did not fail to express their dissatisfaction that we were forced to reach this end.
Democratic Senator Barack Obama credited himself with adding some provisions to the deal, including allowing homeowners to keep their homes and the salary of executives at state-run businesses.
“When taxpayers are asked to take extraordinary measures because of the irresponsibility of some, there is no reason to welcome them.
But these measures are necessary," he said on U.S. television.
Asked on another channel whether he would vote for the proposed plan, his Republican opponent, John McCain, replied, "I'd like to see the details, but I hope so."
“The broad lines I’ve read [show] that it’s something we’re all going to have to digest and with which we’re going to be able to move forward.
The option to do nothing is simply not acceptable,” he said.
The $700 billion plan aims to redeem with taxpayers’ money the dubious, risky and unsellable assets of U.S. financial institutions.
It comes after 14 months of a crisis triggered by the bursting of a real estate bubble that first led to the collapse of risky mortgages (subprimes) before expanding to other more widespread forms of credit securities (PCAAs) and leading to a freeze of liquidity and the rout of banks and financial institutions.
It was a group of elected Republicans who overturned the first draft agreement last week.
We are believed to have come out of this impasse since Democrats accepted that some “toxic” assets of struggling companies are only insured by the government, rather than bought.
In order to round the corners for everyone in Congress, a provision was also added that if the government were to bear losses for five years with this program, it could put in place new taxes to help it recover its bet.
The new plan provides for the payment of a first tranche of $250 billion to which an additional $100 billion can be added if the president deems it necessary.
The payment of another $350 billion should be endorsed by another Congressional vote.
In exchange for his help, Washington will get stakes in the companies it rescues, which will earn dividends in case of profit and which it can resell when the turmoil has passed.
The federal government will have the opportunity to delay foreclosure procedures for dwellings attached to real estate loans covered by this plan, as well as to set limits on compensation and severance pay to managers of affected businesses.
The architects of the plan would like to see it put to the vote of the House of Representatives today, and to that of the Senate on Wednesday.
Despite all their efforts, it is not yet certain that their plan will have the green light.
Indeed, votes continued to rise yesterday against this project, both in the Republican and Democratic camps.
“Obviously, Washington is not listening to you,” Republican Scott Garrett, a member of the House finance committee, told voters.
“Yes, we have a serious financial problem.
Yes, there are solutions.
It’s not about benefiting taxpayers.”
Host of a small group in Congress dubbed “the caucus of skeptics,” Democratic Rep. Brad Sherman presents things differently, but comes to the same conclusion.
“Four hundred eminent economics professors, including three Nobel Prize laureates, have written to us to tell us: Congress is asked not to hurry and to carefully examine the way forward,” he said.
At the same time, in Europe, we once again had proof of the global nature of the crisis.
At the end of an emergency meeting, the three Benelux countries announced the partial nationalization of the Fortis banking group for 11.2 billion euros (16.3 billion US dollars).
The intervention of the governments of Belgium, the Netherlands and Luxembourg had been made necessary after the French bank BNP Paribas announced that it was renouncing to acquire its competitor in full sinking since it lost 2 billion euros (2.9 billion US) in the crisis of risky mortgages in the United States.
Fortis employs 85,000 people and is one of the 20 largest European banks and 10 largest insurers.
"This is not money lost," Dutch Finance Minister Wouter Bos said yesterday.
In exchange, a voting right in the bank and influence is regained.
This is precisely something that savers and households appreciate now that the times are uncertain."
Meanwhile, across the English Channel, the British government seemed on track to nationalize another bank battered by the financial crisis.
According to the British press, the government would take over all outstanding loans at Bradford and Bringley Bank, including more than 41 billion (US$75.5 billion) of real estate loans.
The Spanish bank Santander said yesterday that it would buy the branches and customer accounts of the British bank.
Bradford and Bringley would be the second bank, after Northern Rock, that the British government should nationalize since the beginning of this financial crisis.
