The Psychology of Overbidding: Why Do We Spend More Money?
At auctions, buyers tend to spend more, and overestimate the merchandise.
Researchers in neurology and economics at New York University have managed to update the neurological and economic foundations of this known and seemingly irrational behavior.
According to their study published in the journal Science, human beings do not want to be distanced during this type of competition, such as an auction on eBay, and that is why they even prefer to pay too high a price.
This research attempted to draw up a neurological scheme of this kind of "game" using experimental auctions.
One of the groups of volunteers was playing the lottery, while the other group was participating in a fun auction, while using a functional magnetic resonance (fMRI) process, the researchers were analyzing the active brain domains of the experimental subjects.
In both games, participants were able to win money, but during the auction, an essential element of which is the overbidding of a third, the set under the brain stem, called the striatum, was set in motion intensively when the game was lost.
This part of the brain, along with several other functions, plays a role in the “self-stimulation” mechanism of the nervous system.
This is why, according to the researchers, the rise in prices is explained by the flight in front of the violent reaction of the striatum.
In support of their theories, the economists in this group of researchers carried out financial surveillance analyses.
In these cases, three groups were outbid against a partner, in various circumstances.
They simply informed the control group of the actual value of the product in question, and thus they made their bet.
To another group, they promised that if, in addition, they came out winning the game, then they would receive an additional $15 as a reward.
While the third group received that $15 before the auction, the group members also lost that money, in case they lost the auction.
The difference between these two groups is in fact that the emphasis was placed in one on victory, while in the other, on failure.
