The smart car mimics the theft of the buzzer
What better method would be to develop technologies capable of avoiding an obstacle than the imitation of an existing obstacle detector in nature?
Like, for example, the bees.
In the amazing project presented at CEATEC, taking place in Japan, the buzzing bees gave the Nissan engineers the strategic idea to start, to inspire them on how they should design the next generation of obstacle detectors.
In collaboration with the University of Tokyo, Nissan has built a mini robot car, a bio-inspired BR23C self-controlled robot system, which it has equipped with the qualities of bees, the ultimate goal being to encourage the development of a system capable of avoiding all obstacles.
During its flights, each bee constitutes its own space, oval in shape, which in reality looks a lot like our secure protective shell - explained, during the exhibition, Kazuhhiro Doi, the director of the research and development and technological public relations department of the brand.
The faceted eye of the bee plays a crucial role, since it is able to see in all directions, at an angle of 300 degrees.
To mimic the functions of the faceted eye, the engineers approached the idea of the laser rangefinder.
It identifies obstacles at an angle of 180 degrees and a distance of 2 meters in front of the BR23C, assesses the distances and sends a signal to the on-board microprocessor, which transforms it into an avoidance maneuver immediately.
The perception of the obstacle takes place in a fraction of a second. Then the mini auto robot, imitating the movements of the bee, immediately changes the direction of its wheels by turning it from an angle sufficient to avoid collision.
Unlike any system currently in existence, this avoidance maneuver takes place entirely instinctively.
“If this were not the case, the mini auto robot would not be able to react quickly enough to avoid the obstacle,” said Toshiyuki Andoh, director of the Mobility Laboratory and the Robotic Car Project.
It must react instinctively and instantaneously, since this technology corresponds to the most vulnerable and inner layer of the protective envelope, a layer where for the moment collision is considered inevitable.
This whole process must reflect what the bee does to avoid the other bees.
The process should take place in the blink of an eye.
Unlike bees, the difference cannot go up, down or diagonally, it can only be two-dimensional, and only in the direction in which the wheels can rotate.
In this way, instead of the infinite combinations that the bees have to avoid the other bees, in our case, we could only use the rotary movement, acceleration as well as the slowdown as maneuvers at the disposal of the mini auto robot
The BR23C uses polymer lithium batteries that are lighter and have a larger energy concentrate, which makes their lifespan longer than in the Lithium-ion version.
According to Andoh, it is the instinctive intelligent reaction that is paramount, not the processing of data, let alone the ability to store it.
This mechanism should only process a few incoming signals per second, and react to them.
There is no need to store them and react with intuitive logic based on data from previous manoeuvres, so it only uses a few dozen kilobytes of memory continuously.
There is no need for memory with a capacity of gigabytes, or even megabytes.
This is the first step towards designing a technology for instantaneous avoidance, which Nissan estimates will enter mass-produced cars in the next ten years.
Another application could be its incorporation into the GPS satellite navigation system, so that it can guide the driver to his destination avoiding obstacles in the way.
