In August 2008, domestic industrial sales prices increased by 0.1 percent compared to the previous month, and by 12.9 percent compared to August 2007 - reports the Central Statistical Office of Hungary.
Industrial export sales prices increased by 1.1 per cent compared to July 2008, while compared to a year earlier, they decreased by 3.9 per cent.
As a result of fluctuations in domestic and export prices, industrial production prices increased by 0.7 per cent compared to the previous month, and by 3.2 per cent compared to the previous year.
Domestic industrial sales prices rose only to a lesser extent: by 0.1 percent, compared to the previous month.
Domestic sales prices in the processing industry sectors rose by only 0.1 percent compared to July.
In August 2008, the most significant price increase was observed in the leather goods and footwear manufacturing sector (2.8 per cent), with firstly, the manufacture of bags and belts with a monthly increase of 4.6 per cent, then the production of shoes with a monthly increase of 2.5 per cent.
The higher prices of plastic and chemical raw materials resulted in a significant monthly increase in the prices of the chemicals and products manufacturing sector (1.6 per cent).
This resulted in deflation in oil processing (1.4 per cent), electrical machinery and equipment manufacturing (0.9 per cent), and a minimal increase in wood processing (0.1 per cent).
The prices of paper production, publishing and printing activities have not changed.
Other sectors of the processing industry saw an increase, between 0.2 percent and 0.9 percent.
In the electricity, gas, steam and water supply sectors, representing a significant weight in domestic industrial exploitation, prices rose by 0.3 percent in August, mainly due to the effect of the increase in gas prices implemented by the authorities since 1 July.
In a 12-month comparison, taking into account domestic sales of processing sectors, prices in the oil processing sector experienced the most significant increase (32.4 per cent).
In the metallurgical manufacturing sector, price increases of 13.2 per cent were observed, while in the major food, beverage and tobacco production sector, prices increased by 11 per cent.
Price declines occurred in the textile and textile production sectors (2.5 per cent), as well as in the manufacturing of machinery and electrical appliances (0.3 per cent).
In other sectors of the processing industry, price increases ranged from 0.6 percent to 9.1 percent.
Across the processing industry as a whole, prices increased by 10.2 per cent over the past year.
Prices in the electricity, gas, steam and water supply sectors exceeded those of the previous year by 18.7 percent.
Among the domestic trade groups and according to sector allocation, in August, the most significant monthly price increase (0.7 percent) was in the sectors initiating investment profit.
Prices in the consumer goods production sectors increased by 0.3 per cent, while prices in the energy and material-processing sectors remained unchanged from the previous month.
