MP3 player pointing fingers, they put hearing at risk.
Listening to music at full volume for an extended period using portable music devices such as MP3 players can cause permanent hearing damage.
This is what the European Commission announces, which, in a statement released in Brussels, quotes the opinion of the Scientific Committee, on the unforeseen and recently identified health risks (Csseri) of the EU, published today.
"From this scientific report - we read in the note - it appears that 5-10% of those who, for a period of at least 5 years, listen to music at full volume using portable music devices, for more than one hour per day and per week, risk permanent loss of hearing."
“I am concerned that such a large number of young people who frequently use portable music devices and mobile phones at full volume may unconsciously damage their hearing irreparably,” Kuneva said.
“According to scientific data, this is a clear risk and we need to react quickly.
The most important thing is to raise awareness among consumers and make this information public.
We also need to re-examine existing control systems in the light of scientific opinion, so that they are fully effective and can follow new technologies."
Brussels asked the Independent Scientific Committee to examine the problem, given the intensive use of portable music devices and the increase in the number of young people exposed to the noise they generate.
Scientists confirm that there is good cause for concern, and that the European Commission will now discuss with Member States and other stakeholders what measures could possibly be taken to better protect children and adolescents from exposure to noise from portable music devices and similar devices.
There is already a European safety standard that limits the noise level of portable music devices to 100Db, but there is growing concern about hearing damage that could result from excessive exposure to such noise sources.
It is possible to limit this data by using solutions such as reducing noise exposure levels and duration.
The EU Scientific Committee notes that users of portable music devices, who listen to music at full volume (more than 89 decibels) for 5 hours per week, exceed the limits currently in force regarding the maximum noise level allowed in the workplace.
Those who listen to music in such conditions for extended periods risk permanent loss of hearing after 5 years.
This affects 5-10% of users of these devices, and their number can be quantified at around 2.5 and 10 million people in the EU.
