The elites are in danger.
The phenomenon had already manifested itself a few days ago, with the vote of the House of Representatives, contrary to the $700 billion bailout plan approved by the White House: a significant number of Americans were, and still are, more interested in punishing Wall Street than in saving the American economy.
And it is the New York Times of yesterday that confirms us by communicating that the current crisis divides the Republican Party, even more divided between its old East Coast soul, moderate, favorable to federal institutions as well as to the business community, and its new soul, on the contrary, conservative, hostile to "those of Washington" and to the world of finance, powerful especially in the central and southern states.
The very soul that made itself felt despotically with the vote I was talking about at the beginning.
However, what has just been mentioned is just one example of the changes, of the great changes that the current economic earthquake foretells or already allows to take place: not only in the United States, but throughout the West, and perhaps not only here.
In the United States as in Europe, the crisis seems to accelerate the phenomena hatched for some time, so much so that, in the new climate, they solidify and reveal themselves.
The first of these phenomena is the re-actualization, the extraordinary revival, of the double category sovereign-state, in relation to a kind of renationalization of the economy.
The crisis, in fact, is a crisis of banking-financial institutions that obviously have close relations with foreign countries, but which, above all, are involved on a large scale, the balance sheets of individuals and families who live in a single country, in a single state.
This immediately creates a political problem for those who govern it: that is, how to respond to the difficulties and protests of individuals and families who are also an electorate.
In short, the crisis appears economically global but politically, it is almost only here national.
Political internationalisation seems really out of the question, or does not have much to say: the obvious evidence is provided by the European Union, which, shared as usual, between the various interests and between the various national strategies, fails to decide on any common political line.
And so, it is from the government of each state that everyone expects interventions, rescue and recovery plans, new rules, and above all an affection of credits: when you go through a difficult period, only the states have the economic resources, the mass of financial resources able to try to put things back in place.
They also possess the necessary means and the legitimacy to use them: two resources of inestimable value, elements that no market or international organization can ever have in a similar way.
This new emphasis on the nation-state crisis is, moreover, in perfect harmony with the ever greater importance which the more recent economic developments tend to attribute to a factor quite linked to this element: territoriality.
. Paradoxically, in fact, while we were convinced that we had now entered the realm of the network, of increasingly sophisticated technology, of the non-material, convinced that globalized finance was now destined to dominate the world, we realized in one fell swoop, that our future will have to settle its accounts more and more with the rather unmaterial things, such as water.
Things that can certainly be transported from one place to another on earth, but that are absolutely linked to a limited space, to a territory.
So he who is sovereign certainly has more cards than he who is not, that is to say, he who has the misfortune of living in a place without harvest, without oil and without water.
I now come to the second novelty which, however, foresees a fracture.
Who says Territory, State, Government, inevitably called Politics, and therefore Leadership.
In this respect, the economic crisis seems to produce two convergent phenomena.
On the one hand, the awareness of the objective need for authoritarian leadership, the search for a person who knows how to take charge of the situation.
On the other hand, a wave of discredit for existing leaderships, economic species that have proved inadequate and full of shadows.
And moreover, something even deeper, in a certain sense, even disturbing: a discredit, a suffering, an image of inadequacy, a feeling of remoteness that tends to involve the entire class of directors in an increasing number of Western countries.
Thus the conviction of the various classes increases even more, before the actions are the same ideas of the social elites until now at their peak, their way of listening and being, their culture in the complex acceptance of the term, to have the same time, and to be ever more alien to the opinions of the majorities.
In short, the demand for leadership, feeds underground, a powerful and branched movement of delegitimizations of the ruling classes and traditional political orders, which manifest themselves in the "revolts" improvised electoral or else, in the changes of collective moods of the latter only recently, from the conservative rise in Austria Bavaria, to the fall of the Great rebellion and the fall of the workers.
We have the impression that the traditional elites, their parties, their programs, but also their rites, their newspapers, their accredited intellectuals, their format, someone would say, are finding it increasingly difficult, which is not from today, to understand and therefore to represent the deep layers of Western societies, and that the economic crisis strengthens, increases and potentially agitates in an undisturbed way.
In view of all this, to speak of a current "rebellion of the masses" on the agenda seems frankly exaggerated.
