The superglue to walk on the walls.
Defeat the laws of gravity with a super glue and, in the future, walk on the walls like Spiderman.
This is the goal of various American research centers, and today a team of four institutes has almost succeeded.
With an adhesive measuring just 2.5 square centimeters, the researchers managed to keep a 100-kilogram body glued to a vertical wall.
The American journal Science has published the findings of some researchers from the University of Dayton, Akron, the Georgia Institute of Technology and the Air Force Research Laboratory.
The material, invented by the team of researchers, is an evolution of those we know that use a particular structure of carbon, called carbon nanotubes.
"The glue principle can be imagined as a series of tubes arranged like a stack of spaghetti," explains Zhong Lin Wang of the Georgia Institute of Technology in Atlanta.
Scientists have taken inspiration from the legs of geckos, covered with microscopic hairs that make it possible to ensure a perfect adherence to the animal.
Tests carried out on various materials, such as glass, Teflon, and sandpaper, have shown that the new adhesive is ten times more powerful than the legs of these reptiles, and at the same time, that it “is easily detached from the wall,” says Liming Dai, a researcher at the University of Dayton’s Faculty of Engineering.
WALKING ON WALLS? – “this material could be used as a temporary adhesive,” adds Liming Dai.
Perhaps to walk on walls like Spiderman? Maybe so, but researchers think of a much less fascinating use such as the connection between electronic devices, since carbon nanotubes are conductors of heat and electric current.
Other applications could concern aerospace engineering.
So far, no superheroes.
OTHER RESEARCH- The University of Berkeley, California, is also looking for a new adhesive.
In an article in the American Chemical Society, California researchers presented an adhesive made of microfibers like hair, which cleans itself of dust during movement on a surface to ensure perfect and constant adhesion.
Drugs: Never with fruit juices.
Beware of grapefruit, orange and apple juice.
These drinks, consumed especially in the summer because they are thirst-quenching and rich in vitamins, if combined with certain vital drugs, alter their absorption, amplifying or decreasing, depending on the case, their effectiveness, with even serious consequences for health.
David Nailey, a professor at the University of Western Ontario in London, recalls the risks of fruit juices, whether canned or fresh, if associated with the ingestion of certain drugs; during the 236th national meeting of the American Chemical Society in Philadelphia, he launches a new alarm: just a glass of grapefruit juice, grapefruit and orange juice.
Grapefruit juice has already been heavily criticized as held responsible for increasing the effects of certain antiarrhythmic drugs, antibiotics, anxiolytics, anti-stem and neurological drugs, up to toxic levels.
MEDICATIONS AT RISK- It was the Italian Agency for the drug itself, which had given the news in a newsletter dated two years, warning doctors and patients not to underestimate the danger deriving from this mix and to pay attention to what you drink, if you take drugs such as, for example, Diazepam or Methadone.
NOT PAMPLEMOUS- According to experts, even orange and apple juice contains substances that inhibit drugs.
Long is the list of active ingredients inhibited by grapefruit and other juices.
Michele Carruba, director of the Department of Pharmacology at the Public University of Milan, said: "These findings are generally immediately reported to the various national and international drug agencies who will need to change the information notes of the drugs if necessary.
It is always necessary to read the illustrative papers of the drugs you are taking, and, if something is not clear, do not be impressed, but clearly address the doctor or pharmacist," the expert stressed to the agency Ansa.
The Nobel Prize in Economics was awarded to Paul Krugman.
The Nobel Prize in Economics was awarded to the American Paul Krugman for his research on business models and the location of economic activities.
Krugman, 55, is a neo-Keynesian who teaches at Princeton University and is also a famous New York Times columnist.
Krugman is one of the greatest critics of the Bush administration's solutions in economics and foreign policy.
A few months after the September 2001 attacks, during the days of Enron's bankruptcy, Krugman wrote in an article in the New York Times that the second event would have been more decisive than the first, in terms of consequences on U.S. history.
A prediction that sparked many controversies, and which was blamed on the economist for years, but which has now turned out to be accurate.
“I am surprised and even a little shocked at how quickly the memory of scandals such as the collapse of Enron or Worldcom disappeared from the public’s attention,” Krugman said in a statement.
According to Lorenzo Bini Smaghi of the Executive Committee of the European Central Bank, Krugman is a "high-value economist", but also a very aggressive "disseminator", particularly critical of the Bush administration's excesses of liberalism.
Open Office, here is the third edition of the "anti-Microsoft" package
This is the day of the release of OpenOffice.org.3.0, the open source suite of personal productivity that aims to reach ever more users, from home to office, from professionals to public administration, offering a free alternative to the most famous Microsoft Office.
After almost a year of work, carried out by voluntary developers, supervised by SUN Microsystem, the new Open Office package is shown to the general public with various novelties: from the welcome screen, and the revised interface and became less austere, to others more important, such as the compatibility born for the latest operating system Apple Mac OS X, and the support for the new format ODF.
Open Office has paid particular attention to the interaction with the Office 2007 suite, and it is indeed possible to open documents with the new Microsoft extension (.docx, .xlsx, .pptx.)
Also interesting, some features specific to some modules, such as the one that allows you to reduce the dimensions of PowerPoint presentations, useful for example, to send them by email, or to import PDF files into the graphic design module, maintaining the original appearance of the page.
Also on this front, it is possible to create "Hybrid PDF" documents that link the typical graph of the Adobe format with elements of a spreadsheet or text editor.
The collaboration between several people is an element that has had various improvements within the applications: in the worksheet, various users can intervene, avoiding conflicts on modifications, in the elaboration of texts, because each collaborator is assigned a color of comments for better recognition in the revision phase.
Some companies are even working to bring some of OpenOffice’s features to the web (on the cloud), and in the coming weeks, they are expected to issue the final result.
The Italian version can be downloaded at http://it.openoffice.org/download/3.0.0/download300.htmlet and is added to the English version that has been on the mirror since Friday.
In addition to Windows and Mac OS, the suite is as usual also available for the Linux operating system.
On request, the installation CD can be shipped at home or at the workplace.
And if the theme of gratuitousness can be a means to spread it in the homes, it is precisely in the business, that Open Office the suite tries the great challenge, already being able to count on various projects carried out in the public administration and schools.
Not to mention the realities that offer a training, consultation and assistance service, ideal for small and medium-sized companies, which could also open up to business prospects.
Open Office consists of five main modules: Writer, for equivalent video writing of Word; Calc, is the spreadsheet that aims to replace Excel; Impress, for rival PowerPoint presentations; Dbase, like the famous Access, is the program that allows to work on databases; finally Drwa is the graphical module.
Target for 2008, to reach 5 million downloads, and considering that today there are almost 3 million and 600 miles, it is likely that with the release of the new version, we can even exceed the expected figure
