Students victims of expensive rents, up to 900 euros for a room.
Student housing market is not in crisis
According to the latest survey of the Sunia, the tenant union, renting a single room can cost a student, up to 900 euros in Milan, 700 in Florence, 650 in Naples, 600 in Rome.
"The phenomenon has now reached very serious aspects to the point of excluding entire categories of young people, from the right to study because of the very high overall costs that the families from which they come have to support - explains the head of the Sunia study office, Laura Mariani - in these cities, the high demand from students has so distorted the market that a process of widespread increase has begun for them.
In most cases, rental offers also involve a series of breaches: free, unregistered contracts, no rent limit, sub-rents.
For the Sunia, extraordinary interventions through the revision of the tax are necessary to calm the prices.
Reading the survey in detail, we see that in Milan, for a bed in the Brianza area, it takes about 450 euros; for a single room, we go from a minimum of 650 euros (Black Strip area), to an average value of 800 (Lambiate area, Udine, and Fiera) to a maximum of 900 euros (Vittoria area)
In Florence, a bed costs on average, 350/400 euros, a room about 700 euros.
In Bologna, where students are concentrated in areas close to the University, it takes 250/280 euros for a bed in a double, and from 370 to 500 for a single room.
In Rome, in the areas close to the central universities (San Lorenzo, Piazza Bologna), we ask about 600 euros for a single, 450 for a bed in a double.
Slightly lower values (550 euro for a single) for areas close to other universities (Ostiense and Cinecitt<0xC3><0xA0>).
One can save only if one moves away in the peripheral areas: 300 euros for a bed, and 450 for a single in the Predestina area, Centocell or similar.
In Naples, for a bed you need 300/400 euros, for a simple one, you spend from 400 to 600 euros, with higher prices in the areas Policlinico, Vomero, and Colli Aminei.
In Bari, for a bed, you have to count 250/350 euros, at least 350 for a simple one.
In smaller cities, prices are lower in absolute terms, but they have a major importance in the city economy.
Finally, cities such as Perugia, in which rents are often taken by extra-community students, there is a subsequent anomaly: the rent charged to foreign students is increased by 25/30% compared to that applied to Italians.
Farewell old cinema Paradiso, cities eliminate historic halls.
Historical cinemas are closing in favour of Multiplexes.
“A city without cinemas is a blind city, it’s like a face without eyes.”
The image offered by the director Giuseppe Tornatore, illustrates well what is happening in the great Italian urban centers, but also in the provincial cities,
The process of marginalization of cinemas, with the birth on the periphery of large multi-rooms, and the death of consumption of mono-rooms in the central areas of cities, is one of the major events that seems inevitable and indisputable to us; it also has all the characteristics of a true cultural crime.
To disappear, they are often historical places and full of memory, "it's as if one of my friends disappeared, someone we know, with whom we shared a piece of the way and so many emotions" observes the director of the Nuovo cinéma Paradiso, a film that offers Tornatore 20 years ago, the first Oscar as well as the Grand Prix of the jury of Cannes, and that told the story of the
The figures provided by Anec, the main trade association, mean everything: in the last five years, 316 traditional cinemas have closed, and it is the halls of the main cities that have paid the most: 10 less in Florence, 9 in Milan, Naples, Bologna and Rome, 6 less in Turin, 5 in Palermo.
Among the regions most affected by the closure, the Roman Emilie leads with 82 lost mono cinemas, followed by Tuscany (44) and Lombardy (41).
The proof that confirms that the first responsible for their disappearance is the advent of the multiplex, because it is the three Italian regions that have recorded the most new multi-room cinemas: 195 more screens in Lombardy in the last five years, 81 in Tuscany as in Emilia-Romagna.
"Italian exploitation has developed irrationally," observes Paolo Protti, president of the Anec, "it is useful to build new structures, but it should still guarantee the survival of those that already exist, because when a room closes in a city, these frequenters are not necessarily all willing to go to multiplexes.
Not to mention the lack of deliberation of credit in favor of traders: the previous debt of the State is about 10 million euros.
It is shameful that, from an ethical and moral point of view, the Government does not respect existing laws.
To support the sector, it would take between 16 and 18 million euros per year.
Notable is the case of Bologna, the first Italian city that, worried about these closures, decided to resolve the situation thanks to the signing of a protocol between the City Hall and Anec, the first of its kind in Italy, to defend and promote cinemas in historic centers and on the outskirts.
Among the regulations provided for, there are measures of tax facilities for managers and benefits for the public in terms of mobility: spectators will be able to enter the restricted traffic area, and will have special rates for parking lots and in some parking lots.
"It is an initiative that I like," Giuseppe Tornatore observes "and I hope that other cities will follow the example of Bologna implementing other measures.
However, it is obvious that, to contrast the super power of multiplexes, traditional rooms must also improve the quality of sound and image, as today's audience is more demanding.
The defense of traditional cinema is a theme that for me, has always been important: the closure of the Supercinema of Bagheria, the place of my childhood and adolescence, was the spark that convinced me to make "New Cinema Paradiso" that I had been thinking about for 10 years.
I have been living in Rome for 25 years, and when I pass the Rialto, or the Quirinal of Via Nazionale, now closed, where I have lived so many shared emotions, I turn to the other side so as not to see the signs blackened by dust.
