When the energy is born from the waves, now the big ones are launched.
This is a disproportionate deposit that occupies more than 70% of the planet’s surface and now the world’s major energy companies are discovering it.
Waves, currents, tides, these are the new renewable sources that giants like Chevron have set their eyes on, and are now trying to get their hands on.
The possibility of obtaining energy from the movements of the sea has been studied for hundreds of years now, and in the 1970s, in conjunction with the first oil crisis, research has intensified.
When the price of oil fell, around 1980, the idea of exploiting marine energy was put aside, but now the environmentalist authorities and the new increase in oil give a great boost to the sector.
The World Energy Council (WEC) in London estimated in 2007 that 15% of the world’s electricity needs could be met by swell-of-sea operating systems.
This would be twice the amount produced by nuclear power plants.
And besides, there would be the currents and the tides..
Colossi on the attack.
The first company to focus on marine energy was Enersis, which in 2005 signed an agreement to build a facility in northern Portugal.
When the agreement was announced, it seemed like a real revolutionary step.
Two years on, more and more of these traditional energy companies are relying on marine energy.
“Chevron is currently studying ocean energy technologies,” a spokesman for a company associated with the U.S. oil giant told the Wall Street Journal, “and it is assessing the possibilities of cooperating with us.”
The cooperation in question concerns the obtaining of a deliberate permit by the US Energy Commission, necessary to give rise to a project to exploit marine energy in Alaska.
This is a very interesting signal, especially considering that in Alaska, the US continues to extract oil, and recently President Bush has set up a project for new excavations.
In addition to Chevron, there are Verdant Power Inc. of New York and Ocean Power of New Jersey, which travel the path of energy coming from the sea, and the sums invested to date, although their details are not known, according to observers, an increasing interest.
Technology to be developed.
Experts are talking about a technology still in its infancy, because marine energy does not dispel fears about the environmental impact.
At present, systems such as those in Portugal, or some in Scotland, are small in size and do not seem to create a major problem for the ecosystem.
To produce energy on a large scale, however, it is necessary to use technologies with a higher environmental impact.
“And the choices are diverse: Ocean Power, for example, uses a system of buoys connected to each other.
The wave thrust, which causes the sludge to move up and down, is converted to hydraulic pressure from the pistons and cylinders inside the floats.
The pressure rotates a turbine, which in turn feeds a generator.
The energy is sent to shore through underwater cables.
At the moment, we have four such systems in the project phase, pending a single federal approval, and some of the energy could be used for a military installation.
Verdant Power, on the other hand, is already producing energy for a shopping mall and parking lot using six underwater turbines from New York’s East River.
The movement of the water during the tides, rotates the turbine blades, creating a rotating movement that feeds a generator.
Verdant has announced that it has a long list of customers waiting for the necessary authorizations to draw energy.
After the waves, the tides.
A particular interest, they say at the Institute for Electric Energy Research, deserves the potential of tides right now.
Although it is an intermittent phenomenon, the tide is more predictable from wind, sun, or waves, and therefore more reliable as an energy source.
And it is precisely on tidal energy that states like New York, Maine and Alaska, along with others, look to the coast, invested $7.5 million in 2008 and expect investments of up to $35 million in 2009.
